      <div class="prose">
        <h2>Provenance — what the documents say</h2>
        <p>
          The factory Kardex records engine number 84 578 — matching the P84578 stamped on the case — with
          transmission 29 345, Fjord Green (fjordgrün) paint, and beige leatherette (Kunstleder) interior.
          The car was delivered on 4 August 1959 through Hoffman in New York, on Phönix tires with US
          bumpers. The Reutter body plate carries 108689 and the paint tag reads Farbton R 705. A Texas
          title issued in Houston in January 1974 brackets the start of its long storage.
        </p>
        <div class="callout auth">
          <b>Verification status:</b> matching numbers fully confirmed — engine (Kardex 84 578 vs. case
          stamp P84578) and transmission (Kardex 29 345 vs. gearbox case stamp, photographed 2026-07-16)
          both check out.
        </div>

        <figure>
          <img src="/photos/car/gearbox-stamp-29345.jpg" alt="Transmission case stamp reading 29345, matching the Kardex Getriebe number" />
          <figcaption>The gearbox case stamp — 29345, matching the Kardex Getriebe entry. Closes the transmission side of the matching-numbers verification.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2 id="as-found">How it survived — the family story</h2>
        <p>
          The fullest account of this car's fifty years comes from the family that kept it. The previous
          owner — who inherited the car and later sold it to Rusty — posted the story to the 356 Registry
          forum when he introduced himself to the community. It's reproduced here in summary, with his
          account as the source.
        </p>
        <p>
          The car had been in his family since his father was a small boy — his father was born in 1968, so
          the car predates him. His father grew up sitting behind the wheel pretending it was a racecar. His
          grandfather, a lifelong machinist in Needville, Texas, was — in the family's words — a man who
          "could fix anything, and he tried." That drive led him to collect hundreds of projects over his
          lifetime, this 356 among them.
        </p>
        <p>
          His grandparents divorced early, and his father didn't see his own dad from age 8 to 14. When he
          came back to Texas at 14, the 356 was still there, still running, parked in the machine shop. He
          spent summers there through age 18. Sometime around 1985 the car stopped running and was
          permanently parked — it had originally been promised to him.
        </p>
        <p>
          After it stopped running, the grandfather decided — on a friend's advice — that the car would look
          better in black, and repainted it over its factory Fjord Green. He stripped it down for a full
          restoration, leaving only the bumpers, drivetrain, and wheels on the car. Then, as happened with
          many of his projects, he lost interest, and it sat stripped in the back of the shop for years.
        </p>
