        <p>
          The grandfather was, by the family's account, a tough man to love but an honest one. Going through
          his things after his death, the family found boxes of new parts for the car that he'd never
          opened, and 356 Registry magazines stacked around the shop — some read, some still sealed. An
          uncle recalled offering to help work on the car over the years; the grandfather told him, "you
          aren't worthy of a car like that."
        </p>
        <p>
          The previous owner visited his grandfather in Needville during a cross-country move in August of
          the year before he posted the story. Over dinner that first evening, his grandfather told him he
          wanted him to have the old Porsche. A few days after they left, his grandfather passed away — he'd
          been the last person to see him alive.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sorting the estate, he found the 356 in the dark at the back of the shop — and then discovered a
          second one: a 1958 356A, also Fjord Green, lying on its side at the back of the shop. His
          grandfather had bought it years earlier as a parts car for the '59, and never explained why it
          ended up on its side. Kardex records pulled for both cars confirmed the years and the shared Fjord
          Green. The '59 went home with him, and he started working on it.
        </p>

